Dear Hiring Team,

It is with great enthusiasm that I submit my candidacy for the *Software Developer (.NET)* role with the *American Arbitration Association*. I bring over three years of software engineering experience across cloud-native backend systems, API platforms, and AI-assisted development workflows, along with an MS in Computer Science from Pace University.

At Sperse, I built a cloud-native interaction layer that translated natural-language requests into safe, validated tool calls across 1,000+ endpoints, exposing RESTful APIs aligned with .NET and ASP.NET Core service contracts. I also engineered queue-based background/worker services and data access modules using EF Core patterns for PostgreSQL and MS SQL Server with Data Annotations and FluentValidation guardrails. Most recently, I optimized delivery through CI/CD pipelines, DevOps practices, pull request workflows, and Azure/Docker/Kubernetes deployment standards, reducing end-to-end latency by 60% and LLM API costs by 50%.

Earlier at Qualitest, I developed backend services that mirror this position's core responsibilities: building RESTful APIs, validating request flows, and operating reliable long-running workloads through AWS Step Functions. In parallel, my research work at the Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab strengthened my testing discipline and technical communication, including hands-on model deployment (vLLM and Hugging Face) and workshops for 50+ students on advanced engineering topics.

AAA's mission to lead the world in innovative dispute prevention, mitigation, and resolution strongly resonates with me. I am especially aligned with your values of *integrity* and *exceptional service*, and I would be proud to contribute to technology that keeps conflict resolution fair, efficient, and accessible. I would welcome the opportunity to discuss how my background can support the American Arbitration Association's engineering goals and can be reached at #ph or #eml.

